Create a form library where field paths like "user.address.city" are type-safe.
API:

typescript
type User = {
  name: string;
  address: { city: string; zip: number };
  tags: string[];
};

const form = useForm<User>();
form.register('address.city'); // OK
form.register('address.country'); // Type error
form.setValue('address.zip', 12345); // OK
form.setValue('address.zip', 'abc'); // Type error
Requirements:

Use template literal types and recursive conditional types for path parsing.

Type helper: Path<T> generates all valid paths ("name" | "address.city" | "address.zip" | "tags" | "tags.0").

Type helper: PathValue<T, P> extracts value type at path.

Support nested objects and arrays.
Implementation:

Recursive type that traverses object structure.

Handle array indices (tags.0, tags.1).

Use infer to extract property types at each level.
Tests:

Path generation for complex nested types.

Value type extraction correctness.

Compiler errors for invalid paths.